From: Mykola Lysenko <nickolay.lysenko@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] btrfs: handle 3-device RAID6 without calling the raid6 library

Commit 2790045a62eb ("raid6: warn when using less than four devices")
made raid6_gen_syndrome() WARN when called with less than
RAID6_MIN_DISKS (4) devices, since the library has never supported the
degenerate 3-unit geometry.  btrfs however allows RAID6 chunks with a
single data stripe (btrfs_raid_array sets devs_min = 3 for RAID6), so
any write through the RMW path or any parity scrub of such a chunk now
triggers the warning:

  WARNING: lib/raid/raid6/algos.c:48 at raid6_gen_syndrome+0x4d/0x60
  Workqueue: btrfs-rmw rmw_rbio_work
  Call Trace:
   rmw_rbio+0x810/0xc82
   rmw_rbio_work+0x30/0x34
   process_scheduled_works+0x1cb/0x2ba

Reproducible with fstests btrfs/297 against a 3-device scratch pool
(only on the first raid6 test of a boot -- WARN_ON_ONCE swallows the
rest), verified on both x86-64/KVM and UML.

For a single data stripe the P/Q algorithm degenerates to P = D0 and
Q = g^0 * D0 = D0: both parities are plain copies of the data, as the
offending commit itself points out.  Compute them with memcpy() and
call the library only for geometries it supports.

The recovery helpers (raid6_recov_2data(), raid6_recov_datap()) did not
grow a minimum-disks assertion, so the read-repair path is left
untouched.

Fixes: 2790045a62eb ("raid6: warn when using less than four devices")
Signed-off-by: Mykola Lysenko <nickolay.lysenko@gmail.com>
---
--- a/fs/btrfs/raid56.c
+++ b/fs/btrfs/raid56.c
@@ -1385,6 +1385,30 @@
 	return kmap_local_page(phys_to_page(paddr)) + offset_in_page(paddr);
 }
 
+/*
+ * Generate RAID6 P/Q parity for one vertical step.
+ *
+ * @pointers holds one sector from each data stripe followed by P and Q.
+ *
+ * The raid6 library requires at least RAID6_MIN_DISKS (4) devices, but btrfs
+ * allows RAID6 chunks with a single data stripe (3 devices).  For that
+ * degenerate geometry both P and Q equal the data by definition of the P/Q
+ * algorithm (P is the XOR of one term, Q is g^0 * that term), so fill them
+ * with memcpy() instead of calling the library.
+ */
+static void rbio_gen_syndrome(struct btrfs_raid_bio *rbio, u32 step,
+			      void **pointers)
+{
+	assert_rbio(rbio);
+
+	if (rbio->real_stripes < RAID6_MIN_DISKS) {
+		memcpy(pointers[rbio->nr_data], pointers[0], step);
+		memcpy(pointers[rbio->nr_data + 1], pointers[0], step);
+		return;
+	}
+	raid6_gen_syndrome(rbio->real_stripes, step, pointers);
+}
+
 static void generate_pq_vertical_step(struct btrfs_raid_bio *rbio, unsigned int sector_nr,
 				      unsigned int step_nr)
 {
@@ -1409,8 +1433,7 @@
 		pointers[stripe++] = kmap_local_paddr(
 				rbio_qstripe_paddr(rbio, sector_nr, step_nr));
 
-		assert_rbio(rbio);
-		raid6_gen_syndrome(rbio->real_stripes, step, pointers);
+		rbio_gen_syndrome(rbio, step, pointers);
 	} else {
 		/* raid5 */
 		memcpy(pointers[rbio->nr_data], pointers[0], step);
@@ -2642,9 +2665,8 @@
 						     step_nr, 0));
 
 	if (has_qstripe) {
-		assert_rbio(rbio);
-		/* RAID6, call the library function to fill in our P/Q. */
-		raid6_gen_syndrome(rbio->real_stripes, step, pointers);
+		/* RAID6, fill in our P/Q. */
+		rbio_gen_syndrome(rbio, step, pointers);
 	} else {
 		/* RAID5. */
 		memcpy(pointers[nr_data], pointers[0], step);
